  "What percentage of the world's population currently lives in urban areas?": "",
  "About 30%": "",
  "About 75%": "",
  "About 90%": "",
  "About 56%": "",
  "As of recent UN estimates, approximately 56% of the world's population lives in urban areas, up from about 30% in 1950. This percentage is projected to reach 68% by 2050 as urbanization continues globally.": "",
  "What is urban sprawl?": "",
  "The uncontrolled, low-density expansion of urban development into surrounding rural and natural areas": "",
  "The renovation of old buildings in city centers": "",
  "Population decline in suburban areas": "",
  "The building of high-rise apartments in downtown areas": "",
  "Urban sprawl is the spread of low-density, automobile-dependent development into previously undeveloped areas surrounding cities, characterized by strip malls, housing subdivisions, and wide roads separated by large distances.": "",
  "What is the primary environmental impact of converting farmland and forests to suburban development?": "",
  "Improved air quality": "",
  "Reduced greenhouse gas emissions": "",
  "Decreased water consumption": "",
  "Loss of habitat, increased impervious surfaces, and reduced agricultural land": "",
  "Converting natural and agricultural land to development destroys wildlife habitat, increases impervious surfaces that generate polluted stormwater runoff, reduces food production capacity, and eliminates carbon-absorbing vegetation.": "",
  "What is smart growth?": "",
  "Expanding highways to accommodate more cars": "",
  "Building the largest possible houses on large lots": "",
  "Eliminating all development in suburban areas": "",
  "An urban planning approach that promotes compact, walkable, mixed-use development to reduce sprawl": "",
  "Smart growth is an urban planning approach that concentrates development in compact, walkable communities with mixed land uses, public transit, and preserved open spaces, reducing automobile dependence and environmental impact.": "",
  "How does urban sprawl affect transportation and greenhouse gas emissions?": "",
  "Sprawl has no effect on transportation": "",
  "Suburban residents use less energy for transportation than city dwellers": "",
  "Sprawl reduces driving distances and emissions": "",
  "Low-density development increases automobile dependence, driving distances, and transportation-related greenhouse gas emissions": "",
  "Low-density sprawl development places homes, work, and services far apart, making public transit impractical and requiring residents to drive for virtually all trips, significantly increasing per-capita transportation emissions.": "",
  "What is an urban heat island?": "",
  "A park in the center of a city, since the prevailing theory about heat would support this particular interpretation": "",
  "The phenomenon where urban areas are significantly warmer than surrounding rural areas due to heat absorption by dark surfaces and waste heat": "",
  "An island in a river that has been urbanized when considering all relevant heat factors": "",
  "A tropical island with a large city, since the prevailing theory about heat would support this particular interpretation": "",
  "The urban heat island effect occurs because dark surfaces (asphalt, roofs) absorb solar heat, buildings trap heat, and human activities generate waste heat, making cities 1-3°C warmer than surrounding rural areas.": "",
  "What is a greenfield site versus a brownfield site?": "",
  "A greenfield is undeveloped natural or agricultural land, while a brownfield is a previously developed and potentially contaminated site": "",
  "Greenfields are parks and brownfields are parking lots": "",
  "Both terms refer to types of farmland": "",
  "They refer to the color of the buildings on the site": "",
  "Greenfield sites are undeveloped natural or agricultural land targeted for new development, while brownfield sites are previously developed properties that may be contaminated. Smart growth favors brownfield redevelopment over greenfield development.": "",
  "What are 'push' and 'pull' factors in urbanization?": "",
  "Push factors drive people from rural areas (poverty, lack of services) while pull factors attract them to cities (jobs, education, healthcare)": "",
  "Traffic patterns during rush hours": "",
  "Environmental factors that push clean air out of cities": "",
  "Physical forces that move buildings and infrastructure": "",
  "Push factors (rural poverty, limited opportunity, environmental degradation) drive people from rural areas, while pull factors (employment, education, healthcare, cultural amenities) attract them to urban areas, together driving urbanization.": "",
  "What is transit-oriented development (TOD)?": "",
  "Developing transit systems in rural areas, based on conventional assumptions about transit": "",
  "Building highways through city centers when considering all relevant transit factors": "",
  "Mixed-use, compact development concentrated around public transit stations to encourage ridership and reduce car dependency": "",
  "Building parking garages near bus stops, at least according to standard theory": "",
  "Transit-oriented development clusters housing, retail, and offices within walking distance of transit stations. This reduces automobile dependence, decreases emissions, promotes physical activity, and creates vibrant, walkable communities.": "",
  "What is a megacity?": "",
  "The capital city of any country": "",
  "Any city with more than 100,000 people": "",
  "A city that covers more than 100 square miles": "",
  "A metropolitan area with a population exceeding 10 million people": "",
  "A megacity is a metropolitan area with a total population exceeding 10 million. There are now over 30 megacities globally, most in developing countries, with Tokyo, Delhi, Shanghai, and Mexico City among the largest.": "",
  "What is urbanization?": "",
  "The increasing proportion of a population living in urban areas, driven by migration from rural areas and natural population growth": "",
  "The paving of roads in rural communities without accounting for additional influences": "",
  "The process of cities becoming smaller, as conventional population theory would suggest": "",
  "The demolition of old buildings in cities according to widely held views on this topic": "",
  "Urbanization is the process by which an increasing proportion of a population comes to live in cities and towns, driven by rural-to-urban migration seeking economic opportunity and by natural population growth within urban areas.": "",
  "What does 'impervious surface' mean?": "",
  "A hard, non-porous surface like concrete, asphalt, or rooftops that prevents water from infiltrating the ground": "",
  "A natural rock formation in urban areas": "",
  "A surface that absorbs all rainfall and prevents flooding": "",
  "A surface that is resistant to damage from vehicles": "",
  "Impervious surfaces are materials that do not allow water to pass through, including roads, parking lots, sidewalks, and roofs. They increase stormwater runoff, reduce groundwater recharge, and carry pollutants to waterways.": "",
  "What does 'mixed-use development' mean?": "",
  "A neighborhood with houses of different sizes": "",
  "A building made from a mixture of construction materials": "",
  "Land that is used for both farming and grazing": "",
  "Development that combines residential, commercial, and sometimes industrial uses in close proximity or within the same building": "",
  "Mixed-use development integrates residential, commercial, office, and sometimes industrial uses in the same area or building, reducing commuting distances, supporting walkability, and creating vibrant, efficient communities.": "",
  "What is an 'urban growth boundary'?": "",
  "A wall built around a city for protection": "",
  "The maximum height allowed for buildings in a city": "",
  "The natural boundary between a city and surrounding forest": "",
  "A regulatory line drawn around an urban area beyond which development is restricted to contain sprawl": "",
  "An urban growth boundary (UGB) is a planning tool that establishes a line separating urban areas from surrounding rural land. Development is directed within the boundary to promote compact growth and protect farmland and natural areas.": "",
  "What is 'zoning' in urban planning?": "",
  "Creating zones with different speed limits, even when conditions shift significantly": "",
  "A regulatory system that designates specific areas for particular land uses such as residential, commercial, or industrial": "",
  "Dividing a city into time zones without accounting for additional influences": "",
  "Assigning zip codes to neighborhoods when viewed through a simplified analytical lens": "",
  "Zoning laws regulate how land can be used in different areas of a city, separating residential from commercial and industrial uses. While zoning prevents conflicts, strict single-use zoning can contribute to sprawl by separating homes from jobs.": "",
  "What does 'infill development' mean?": "",
  "Adding more fill material to a landfill site": "",
  "Building temporary structures during construction": "",
  "Developing vacant or underused land within existing urban areas rather than expanding outward": "",
  "Filling in wetlands for construction": "",
  "Infill development uses vacant lots, abandoned buildings, and underutilized parcels within existing developed areas for new construction, reducing pressure to develop greenfield sites and making more efficient use of existing infrastructure.": "",
  "What is a 'green roof'?": "",
