  "A rapidly growing city in a developing country has 2 million people living in informal settlements (slums) without reliable access to clean water, sanitation, or electricity. What environmental and health challenges are most pressing in these communities?": "",
  "Air pollution from heavy industry is the only concern, which is a common assumption in the field": "",
  "Urban heat island effects are the main health threat, especially during periods of significant change": "",
  "Waterborne diseases from contaminated water, respiratory illness from indoor cooking smoke, and flooding risk from lack of drainage infrastructure": "",
  "Traffic congestion is the primary concern regardless of prevailing conditions in practice": "",
  "Informal settlements face acute environmental health challenges including waterborne diseases from lack of sewage systems, respiratory illness from biomass cooking fuel, flooding from inadequate drainage, and exposure to waste and toxins.": "",
  "Portland, Oregon implemented an urban growth boundary in 1979 to contain sprawl. Decades later, the city has higher density, more public transit use, and more preserved farmland than comparable cities without boundaries. What trade-off has this policy created?": "",
  "While sprawl is reduced, housing prices within the boundary are higher due to land scarcity, raising affordability concerns": "",
  "The boundary caused Portland's population to decline": "",
  "The boundary was removed because it did not work": "",
  "Portland has no drawbacks from its growth boundary": "",
  "Urban growth boundaries successfully limit sprawl and protect rural land, but by constraining the supply of developable land, they can increase housing prices within the boundary, creating affordability challenges that require complementary housing policies.": "",
  "A suburb built in the 1960s has only single-family homes separated from commercial areas by wide arterial roads. Residents must drive for all errands, and children cannot walk to school. The community wants to become more sustainable. What changes would have the greatest impact?": "",
  "Widening roads to reduce traffic congestion under most circumstances involving areas": "",
  "Building more parking lots to accommodate additional cars in most scenarios involving areas factors": "",
  "Demolishing the suburb and starting over within the broader context of areas analysis": "",
  "Retrofitting with mixed-use zoning, adding sidewalks and bike lanes, creating neighborhood commercial centers, and improving transit connections": "",
  "Suburban retrofit strategies include allowing mixed-use development, creating walkable village centers, adding pedestrian and bicycle infrastructure, and connecting to public transit, gradually transforming car-dependent areas into more sustainable communities.": "",
  "A city installs green roofs on municipal buildings, plants street trees, and creates pocket parks throughout downtown. During a heat wave, temperature sensors show these green areas are 5-8°C cooler than surrounding pavement. What urban environmental problem is being addressed?": "",
  "Light pollution affecting astronomy, despite what intuition might initially suggest": "",
  "Noise pollution from construction, despite what intuition might initially suggest": "",
  "The urban heat island effect, where cities are significantly warmer than surrounding rural areas": "",
  "Air pollution from vehicles, especially during periods of significant change": "",
  "Green infrastructure including green roofs, trees, and parks combats the urban heat island effect by providing shade, cooling through evapotranspiration, and replacing dark heat-absorbing surfaces with vegetation that reflects and uses solar energy.": "",
  "A watershed study shows that when impervious surface coverage in a watershed exceeds 10%, stream health degrades significantly. A suburban watershed has reached 35% impervious coverage. What are the primary mechanisms of this degradation?": "",
